Rationale — Why this license

WoWSP is developed in the open: the full source is publicly readable, and the
Additional Use Grant above already grants SySL-1.0 equivalent rights for all
internal, academic, government, educational, and non-commercial use. The
Business Source License 1.1 is used here for a specific, narrow purpose — not
to extract rent, but to protect the work and its community until it fully
opens up.

1. Prevent parasitic re-packaging. The hard part of this project — the replay
   parser, the game-install detection (official / Steam / Lesta / 360), the
   three.js holographic map renderer, and the transparent in-game overlay — is
   difficult to recreate but trivial to re-brand. The BSL production-use
   restriction stops a third party from taking the work, wrapping it under a
   new name, and selling it as their own hosted service without contributing
   anything back.

2. Stability over throughput. A permissive license today would invite
   high-volume, low-quality contributions that would still have to be reviewed
   and rejected, draining the very capacity the project depends on. The
   contribution policy (see CONTRIBUTING.md) deliberately maintains a high
   merge bar.

3. A hard, time-boxed commitment to openness. The Change Date above is binding:
   on 2030-01-01 the entire Licensed Work — every version released under this
   License — automatically converts to the Synthetic Source License (SySL-1.0),
   for everyone and every use, with no restrictions and no commercial license
   required.

Important: opening the license on the Change Date does NOT open the merge bar.
After 2030-01-01 the code is SySL-1.0, but the contribution policy, the PR
review standards, and any CLA requirement remain exactly as they are today.
A more permissive license never means a lower quality gate.
